&gt; It seems that there should be a distinction between machines
&gt; owned and used by the company and those that are providing
&gt; a relay/gateway for email systems.

Rick:

    The conversations are probably buried back in 1986 when .NET was
created.

    The idea was that there are certain machines which provide a network
service which is recognized independent of the company that provides them.
For example, the NSFNET backbone has been administered by two entirely
different groups (the initial backbone by UIUC/Cornell, the new backbone
by MERIT).  Another example is CSNET, which is a organization independent
of the company which provides the service (BBN).

    An advantage of this scheme is that if, for some reason, the operator
of the service should change (for example, the service is contracted to
someone else or a Wall Street raid causes the provider company to be
absorbed into another company), the domain name of the service (which has
not changed) is unaffected.

Craig

